         <abstract>
            <p>Several observations are made about a recently proposed semi-infinite programming (SIP) method for computation of linear Chebyshev approximations to complex-valued functions. A particular discretization of the SIP problem is shown to be equivalent to replacing the usual absolute value of a complex number with related estimates, resulting in a class of quasi-norms on the complex number field $\mathbf{C}$, and consequently a class of quasi-norms on the space $C(Q)$ consisting of all continuous functions defined on $Q \subset \mathbf{C}, Q$ compact. These quasi-norms on $C(Q)$ are estimates of the $L_\infty$ norm on $C(Q)$ and are useful because the best approximation problem in each quasi-norm can be solved by solving (i) an ordinary linear program if $Q$ is finite or (ii) a simplified SIP if $Q$ is not finite.</p>
          </abstract>
